eenth century, charting the rise and fall of different Islamic navies. It focuses on strategy, examining the development and implementation of naval policy and exploring the technology that supported it. It considers the wars Islamic navies participated in, covers all the areas in which Islamic navies operated, and relates Islamic naval power to wider international power politics. The book highlights in particularthe importance of the large Ottoman navy, which influenced and gave a lead to other Islamic naval powers. PHILIP MACDOUGALL was formerly a Lecturer in the Department of Economic History at the University of Kent. He isthe author and editor of several books on maritime history, including The Naval Mutinies of 1797 (Boydell, 2011) and Naval Resistance to Britain's Growing Power in India, 1660-1800 (Boydell, 2014).  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aSea-powerzIslamic countries. 4aMaritime History. 4aMilitary History. 4aModern History. 7aHISTORY / Military / Naval.2bisacsh  aAge of Fighting Sail.  aIndian Ocean.  aIslamic Seapower.  aIslamic States.  aMediterranean.  aNaval Campaigns.  aNaval History.  aNaval Power.  aNaval Technology.  aNaval Warfare.  aOttoman Empire.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311143130740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781787441576?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781787441576423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781787441576/original  a978-3-11-143130-7  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles